WEBVTT

00:17.380 --> 00:18.460
CHAPTER I

00:18.970 --> 00:24.500
I am by birth a Genovese, and my family is one of the most distinguished of that Republic.

00:25.300 --> 00:31.040
My ancestors had been for many years counselors and syndics, and my father had filled several

00:31.040 --> 00:36.520
public situations with honor and reputation. He was respected by all who knew him for his

00:36.520 --> 00:42.500
integrity and indefatigable attention to public business. He passed his younger days perpetually

00:42.500 --> 00:47.320
occupied by the affairs of his country. A variety of circumstances had prevented his

00:47.320 --> 00:52.160
marrying early, nor was it until the decline of life that he had become a husband and the

00:52.160 --> 00:58.380
father of a family. As the circumstances of his marriage illustrate his character, I cannot

00:58.380 --> 01:03.660
refrain from relating them. One of his most intimate friends was a merchant who, from

01:03.660 --> 01:09.400
a flourishing state, fell through numerous mischances into poverty. This man, whose name

01:09.400 --> 01:14.260
was Beaufort, was of a proud and unbending disposition, and could not bear to live in

01:14.260 --> 01:18.320
poverty and oblivion in the same country where he had formerly been distinguished for his

01:18.320 --> 01:24.020
rank and magnificence. Having paid his debts, therefore, in the most honorable manner, he

01:24.020 --> 01:29.200
retreated with his daughter to the town of Lucerne, where he lived unknown and in wretchedness.

01:30.100 --> 01:35.400
My father loved Beaufort with the truest friendship, and was deeply grieved by his retreat in these

01:35.400 --> 01:41.140
unfortunate circumstances. He bitterly deplored the false pride which led his friend to a

01:41.140 --> 01:46.460
conduct so little worthy of the affection that united them. He lost no time in endeavoring

01:46.460 --> 01:51.320
to seek him out, with the hope of persuading him to begin the world again through his credit

01:51.320 --> 01:57.000
and assistance. Beaufort had taken effectual measures to conceal himself, and it was ten

01:57.000 --> 02:02.660
months before my father discovered his abode. Overjoyed at this discovery, he hastened to

02:02.660 --> 02:08.200
the house which was situated in a mean street near the Reuss. But when he entered, misery

02:08.200 --> 02:13.960
and despair alone welcomed him. Beaufort had saved but a very small sum of money from the

02:13.960 --> 02:18.320
lack of his fortunes, but it was sufficient to provide him with sustenance for some months,

02:18.620 --> 02:23.040
and in the meantime he hoped to procure some respectable employment in a merchant's house.

02:23.800 --> 02:29.360
The interval was, consequently, spent in inaction. His grief only became more deep and rankling

02:29.360 --> 02:34.960
when he had leisure for reflection, and at length it took so fast hold of his mind that

02:34.960 --> 02:39.400
at the end of three months he lay on a bed of sickness incapable of any exertion.

02:40.420 --> 02:45.060
His daughter attended him with the greatest tenderness, but she saw with despair that

02:45.060 --> 02:49.800
their little fund was rapidly decreasing, and that there was no other prospect of support.

02:50.440 --> 02:55.520
But Carolyn Beaufort possessed a mind of an uncommon mold, and her courage rose to support

02:55.520 --> 03:01.640
her in her adversity. She procured plain work, she plated straw, and by various means contrived

03:01.640 --> 03:04.420
to earn a pittance scarcely sufficient to support life.

03:05.340 --> 03:10.380
Several months passed in this manner. Her father grew worse, her time was more entirely

03:10.380 --> 03:16.020
occupied in attending him, her means of subsistence decreased, and in the tenth month her father

03:16.020 --> 03:21.620
died in her arms, leaving her an orphan and a beggar. This last blow overcame her, and

03:21.620 --> 03:27.240
she knelt by Beaufort's coffin, weeping bitterly, when my father entered the chamber. He came

03:27.240 --> 03:32.600
like a protecting spirit to the poor girl who committed herself to his care, and after

03:32.600 --> 03:37.400
the interment of his friend he conducted her to Geneva and placed her under the protection

03:37.400 --> 03:41.800
of a relation. Two years after this event Carolyn became his wife.

03:43.340 --> 03:48.180
There was a considerable difference between the ages of my parents, but this circumstance

03:48.180 --> 03:53.280
seemed to unite them only closer in bonds of devoted affection. There was a sense of

03:53.280 --> 03:57.400
justice in my father's upright mind which rendered it unnecessary that he should approve

03:57.400 --> 04:02.960
highly to love strongly. Perhaps during former years he had suffered from the late discovered

04:02.960 --> 04:08.260
unworthiness of one beloved and so was disposed to set a greater value on tried worth.

04:09.240 --> 04:13.500
There was a show of gratitude and worship in his attachment to my mother, differing

04:13.500 --> 04:18.260
wholly from the doting fondness of age, for it was inspired by reverence for her virtues

04:18.260 --> 04:24.160
and a desire to be the means of, in some degree, recompensing her for the sorrows she had endured,

04:24.160 --> 04:30.120
but which gave inexpressible grace to his behavior to her. Everything was made to yield

04:30.120 --> 04:36.200
to her wishes and her convenience. He strove to shelter her, as a fair exotic as sheltered

04:36.200 --> 04:41.160
by the gardener, from every rougher wind and to surround her with all that could tend to

04:41.160 --> 04:46.600
excite pleasurable emotion in her soft and benevolent mind. Her health, and even the

04:46.600 --> 04:51.100
tranquility of her hitherto constant spirit, had been shaken by what she had gone through.

04:52.120 --> 04:57.080
During the two years that it elapsed, previous to their marriage, my father had gradually

04:57.080 --> 05:01.540
relinquished all his public functions, and immediately after their union they sought

05:01.540 --> 05:06.020
the pleasant climate of Italy and the change of scene and interest attendant on a tour

05:06.020 --> 05:09.920
through that land of wonders as a restorative for her weakened frame.

05:12.600 --> 05:18.460
From Italy they visited Germany and France. I, their eldest child, was born at Naples

05:18.460 --> 05:23.340
and as an infant accompanied them in their rambles. I remained for several years their

05:23.340 --> 05:28.140
only child. Much as they were attached to each other, they seemed to draw inexhaustible

05:28.140 --> 05:33.640
stores of affection from a very mine of love to bestow them upon me. My mother's tender

05:33.640 --> 05:38.700
caresses and my father's smile of benevolent pleasure while regarding me are my first recollections.

05:39.720 --> 05:44.720
I was their plaything and their idol, and something better, their child, the innocent

05:44.720 --> 05:49.540
and helpless creature bestowed upon them by Heaven, whom to bring up to good and whose

05:49.540 --> 05:54.680
future lot it was in their hands to direct to happiness or misery according as they fulfilled

05:54.680 --> 05:59.480
their duties toward me. With this deep consciousness of what they owed towards the being to which

05:59.480 --> 06:04.480
they had given life, added to the active spirit of tenderness that animated both, it may be

06:04.480 --> 06:09.200
imagined that while during every hour of my infant life I received a lesson of patience,

06:09.200 --> 06:14.760
of charity and of self-control, and was so guided by a silken cord that all seemed but

06:14.760 --> 06:16.520
one train of enjoyment to me.

06:17.620 --> 06:22.340
For a long time I was their only care. My mother had much desired to have a daughter,

06:22.640 --> 06:28.380
but I continued their single offspring. When I was about five years old, while making an

06:28.380 --> 06:32.860
excursion beyond the frontiers of Italy, they had passed a week on the shores of the Lake

06:32.860 --> 06:37.580
of Como. Their benevolent disposition often made them enter the cottages of the poor.

06:37.580 --> 06:42.900
This, to my mother, was more than a duty, it was a necessity, a passion, remembering

06:42.900 --> 06:48.200
what she had suffered and how she had been relieved. For her to act in her turn the guardian

06:48.200 --> 06:49.580
angel to the afflicted.

06:51.260 --> 06:55.620
During one of their walks a poor cot in the foldings of a veil attracted their notice

06:55.620 --> 07:00.580
as being singularly disconsolate, while the number of half-clothed children gathered about

07:00.580 --> 07:05.680
it spoke of penury of its worst shape. One day, when my father had gone by himself to

07:05.680 --> 07:09.360
Milan, my mother accompanied by me visited this abode.

07:10.340 --> 07:15.520
She found a peasant and his wife hard working, bent down by care and labor, distributing

07:15.520 --> 07:20.960
a scanty meal to five hungry babes. Among these there was one which attracted my mother

07:20.960 --> 07:26.420
far above all the rest. She appeared of a different stock. The four others were dark-eyed,

07:26.600 --> 07:32.000
hardy little vagrants. This child was thin and very fair. Her hair was the brightest

07:32.000 --> 07:36.580
living gold, and despite the poverty of her clothing, seemed to set a crown of distinction

07:36.580 --> 07:41.940
on her head. Her brow was clear and ample, her blue eyes cloudless, and her lips and

07:41.940 --> 07:47.600
the molding of her face so expressive of sensibility and sweetness that none could behold her without

07:47.600 --> 07:53.120
looking on her as of a distinct species, a being heaven-sent, and bearing a celestial

07:53.120 --> 07:54.600
stamp in all her features.

07:55.680 --> 08:00.420
The peasant woman, perceiving that my mother fixed eyes of wonder and admiration on this

08:00.420 --> 08:06.060
lovely girl, eagerly communicated her history. She was not her child, but the daughter of

08:06.060 --> 08:12.240
a Milanese noblewoman. Her mother was a German and had died on giving her birth. The infant

08:12.240 --> 08:17.480
had been placed with these good people to nurse. They were better off then. They had

08:17.480 --> 08:22.580
not been long married, and their eldest child was but just born. The father of their charge

08:22.580 --> 08:27.600
was one of those Italians nursed in the memory of the antique glory of Italy, one among

08:27.600 --> 08:33.600
the sciavi Agnor Frumenti, who exerted himself to obtain the liberty of his country. He became

08:33.600 --> 08:38.040
the victim of its weakness. Whether he had died or still lingered in the dungeons of

08:38.040 --> 08:43.220
Austria was not known. His property was confiscated. His child became an orphan and a beggar.

08:44.240 --> 08:48.800
She continued with her foster parents, and bloomed in their rude abode, fairer than a

08:48.800 --> 08:54.840
garden rose among dark-leaved brambles. When my father returned from Milan, he found, playing

08:54.840 --> 08:59.480
with me in the hall of our villa, a child fairer than the pictured cherub, a creature

08:59.480 --> 09:04.180
who seemed to shed radiance from all her looks, and whose form and motions were lighter than

09:04.180 --> 09:07.960
the chamois of the hills. The apparition was soon explained.

09:08.680 --> 09:13.060
With his permission, my mother prevailed on her rustic guardians to yield their charge

09:13.060 --> 09:17.900
to her. They were fond of the sweet orphan. Her presence had seemed a blessing to them,

09:17.980 --> 09:22.140
but it would be unfair to her to keep her in poverty and want when Providence offered

09:22.140 --> 09:27.520
her such powerful protection. They consulted their village priest, and the result was that

09:27.520 --> 09:33.360
Elizabeth Levenza became the inmate of my parents' house, my more than sister, the beautiful

09:33.360 --> 09:36.400
and adored companion of all my occupations and my pleasures.

09:37.200 --> 09:41.680
Everyone loved Elizabeth. The passionate and almost reverential attachment with which all

09:41.680 --> 09:47.400
regarded her became, while I shared it, my pride and my delight. On the evening previous

09:47.400 --> 09:52.400
to her being brought to my home, my mother said playfully, I have a present for my victor.

09:52.580 --> 09:57.560
Tomorrow he shall have it. And when, on the morrow, she presented Elizabeth to me as her

09:57.560 --> 10:02.880
promised gift, I, with childish seriousness, interpreted her words literally, and looked

10:02.880 --> 10:08.840
upon Elizabeth as mine, mine to protect, love, and cherish. All praises I bestowed on her

10:08.840 --> 10:14.420
I received as made to a possession of my own. We called each other familiarly by the name

10:14.420 --> 10:20.160
of cousin. No word, no expression could body forth the kind of relation in which she stood

10:20.160 --> 10:24.520
to me, my more than sister, since till death she was to be mine only.

